Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Preliminary hearing on June 20, 2022 at 10:30 am.

03:15 PM Defendant Steven Carl Wahlborg in the Pepin County courtroom by zoom technology.  Attorney Dennis Michael Melowski appeared by zoom technology by video means. Attorney Jon D. Seifert appeared by phone means for Plaintiff State of Wisconsin.  Mr. Melowski filed a motion to modify bond to allow driving.  The State objects to that motion due to Mr. Wahlborg's history, 6 prior convictions on his record.  State would ask the Court to maintain the bond conditions as set.  Mr. Melowski addresses Mr. Wahlborg is on alcohol monitoring 24/7. If there is any violation, the Court would be notified immediately.  We are seeking the ability for him to drive simply for work obligations and family care obligations.  He understands if the Court would grant his request, he would be unable to drive for social reasons.  He is always dependent on others taking him to or from work.  It would be counter productive for bond conditions to cost Mr. Wahlborg his employment when we have the capability to monitor him for alcohol consumption.  The Court will grant the motion to allow you to drive to your job site and back home.  The 2nd thing, it would be counter productive to be a negative influence on your children, so the 2nd condition of this order you may drive your children to and from school, to and from their mother's home in Nekoosa.  Court denies the extra curricular activities.  If you can get specifics, we can talk about it.  #1 you only drive legally registered vehicles.  #2 the legally registered vehicle you are driving will be covering you when you drive it.  #3 If you have an occupational license, only drive within your hours.  Mr. Wahlborg took care of the registration issue almost immediately upon release from custody.  His registration is back to valid and has taken care of the insurance issue as well.  There will be zero modification to the sober link requirement.  Court asks Mr. Melowski to provide a modified bond form to the Pepin County Sheriff's Dept. forthwith.  Mr. Melowski requests a PH and waives time limits.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for June 20, 2022 at 10:30 am.

11:00 AM Defendant Steven Carl Wahlborg appeared by video means from the Pepin County Jail. Attorney Jon D. Seifert appeared by phone means for Plaintiff State of Wisconsin.  At yesterday's hearing it was represented to the Court if Mr. Wahlborg was able to secure a monitoring device for his sobriety the State would be willing to amend to a signature bond.  Is that still the State's position?  It is if he his being daily monitored with CJS and also asked yesterday the Court consider no operation of motor vehicle.  The record indicates he has not been refrained from driving after drinking.  Ms. Berning confirms CJS is willing to monitor Mr. Wahlborg and have him set up for sober link and has additional forms to complete if he's released.  He has paid for the deposit.  Court will release you on the conditions of release:  monitored for your alcohol intake and sobriety by a sober link device.  If you test positive for any alcohol, Ms. Berning will make a request to immediately return to jail by a warrant.  The other part of Mr. Seifert's request for protection of public is granted.  You must refrain from driving any motor vehicle.  The AIA is scheduled for 4/5/2022.
